article.description:
Yolanda Griffith scored 18 points to
help Sacramento beat Minnesota 74-66 on Thursday night.
article.headline: Playoff-bound Monarchs fend off pesky Lynx
article.linkText: Playoff-bound Monarchs blow big lead, fend off Lynx
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Yolanda Griffith scored 18 points to
help the Sacramento Monarchs hold off a strong rally by Minnesota
and beat the Lynx 74-66 on Thursday night.

Kara Lawson had 14 points and Rebecca Brunson added 10 points
and 11 rebounds for the defending WNBA champion Monarchs (21-12),
who allowed an 18-point fourth quarter to shrink to four with 1:59
left.

It took a 3-pointer from Nicole Powell with 40 seconds left to
finally seal the game.

"It's very disturbing," Sacramento coach John Whisenant said
of his team's tendency to let big leads slip away. "We're having
trouble keeping our focus -- this time a year ago, we weren't having
this problem."

Seimone Augustus led Minnesota (10-23) with 31 points, including
going 13-for-13 from the free throw line. Nicole Ohlde was the only
other Lynx player in double figures with 11.

Sacramento was able to control the paint, outscoring the Lynx
42-22 and outrebounding Minnesota 46-40.

"We got a little lackadaisical," Brunson said. "We've been
doing that often this season -- we have to keep our intensity up.
Come playoff time, were not going to be able to have those
lapses."

The Monarchs will play at the winner of Sunday's game between
Houston and Seattle in the postseason opener Aug. 17.

Sacramento used a 12-2 run midway through the second quarter to
take a 34-22 lead. The Lynx shot just 31.3 percent from the field
in the first half, going just 6-for-24 at one point.

Augustus tried to keep Minnesota in the game, scoring 26 of the
Lynx's 41 points in the second half.

"We tried to get to the line. We tried to put more pressure on
the ball," Minnesota interim coach Carolyn Jenkins said, "and we
fought back against the defending champs. But it's on us to do it
for 40 minutes."
